  "prompt": "What was the French New Wave?",
  "response": "The French New Wave (Nouvelle Vague) was an influential film movement that emerged in France during the late 1950s and 1960s. Key characteristics include:\n\n1. Origins\n- Developed by young film critics turned directors\n- Centered in Paris, primarily associated with the magazine Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma\n- Key directors: Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut, Jean-Luc Godard, Claude Chabrol, Eric Rohmer\n\n2. Stylistic Innovations\n- Rejected traditional Hollywood storytelling\n- Used handheld cameras for more natural, spontaneous filming\n- Incorporated jump cuts and non-linear narratives\n- Emphasized personal, autobiographical storytelling\n\n3. Philosophical Approach\n- Challenged conventional filmmaking techniques\n- Emphasized director's personal vision (auteur theory)\n- Often explored themes of youth, alienation, and social change\n\n4. Landmark Films\n- \"The 400 Blows\" (Truffaut, 1959)\n- \"Breathless\" (Godard, 1960)\n- \"Cleo from 5 to 7\" (Agn\u00e8s Varda, 1962)\n\n5. Global Impact\n- Revolutionized cinema worldwide\n- Influenced future generations of filmmakers\n- Expanded understanding of film as an art form\n\nThe movement significantly transformed modern cinema's artistic and technical approaches.",
